ἐθησαυρίσατε] Absolute, as in Luke xii. 21 οὕτως ὁ θησαυρίζων ἑαυτῷ, 2 Cor. xii. 14. In Matt. vi. 19 we have the full phrase μὴ θησαυρίζετε θησαυρούς, cf. Rom. ii. 5 θησαυρίζεις σεαυτῷ ὀργὴν ἐν ἡμέρα ὀργῆς, Prov. i. 18 οἱ φόνου μετέχοντες θησαυρίζουσιν ἑαυτοῖς κακά, Amos 111. 10, Tobit iv. 9, Psalm. Sol. iX. 9. ‘The aor. is used as 11 from the standing- point 01 the day of judgment‚ looking back over this life,’ Alf. Perhaps it is more correct to say that it refers back to the perfects σέσηπε, κατίωται. The laying up 01 treasures is anterior to these. The word ἐθησαυρίσατε is pregnant with irony: ‘Yon heap up treasure, but the time for enjoying such treasure has come to an end, it is now only a treasure of wrath in the day 01 wrath.' For the asyndeton 01. below v, 6.
